The paper deals with rank aggregation systems, which involve collecting and processing ordinal preferences from individuals. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category, which deals with the efficient organization and manipulation of data. Additionally, the paper proposes a data-driven approach to rank-breaking, which involves using the topology of the collected data to produce accurate and consistent estimates. This suggests that the paper could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) categories, which deal with developing algorithms that can learn from data. The paper also discusses the error bounds and complexity of the proposed approach, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category. Finally, the paper's focus on pairwise comparisons and comparison graphs suggests that it could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category, which deals with the analysis and modeling of social networks.
